The divisors of 6 are \(\pm 1, \pm 2, \pm 3, \pm 6\). We need to find all ordered triplets \((r, s, t)\) of distinct divisors of 6 such that their product \(rst = -6\). For each valid triplet, we compute \(a = -(r + s + t)\) and \(b = rs + rt + st\). The valid triplets \((r, s, t)\) that satisfy \(rst = -6\) are: 1. \((6, 1, -1)\) 2. \((3, 1, -2)\) 3. \((3, -1, 2)\) 4. \((-3, 1, 2)\) 5. \((-3, -1, -2)\) 6. \((2, 1, -3)\) 7. \((2, -1, 3)\) 8. \((-2, 1, 3)\) 9. \((-2, -1, -3)\) 10. \((1, 2, -3)\) 11. \((1, -2, 3)\) 12. \((-1, 2, 3)\) 13. \((-1, -2, -3)\) For each triplet, we compute \(a\) and \(b\): 1. \((6, 1, -1)\) gives \(a = -6\), \(b = -1\) 2. \((3, 1, -2)\) gives \(a = -2\), \(b = -5\) 3. \((3, -1, 2)\) gives \(a = -4\), \(b = 1\) 4. \((-3, 1, 2)\) gives \(a = 0\), \(b = -7\) 5. \((-3, -1, -2)\) gives \(a = 6\), \(b = 11\) 6. \((2, 1, -3)\) gives \(a = 0\), \(b = -7\) 7. \((2, -1, 3)\) gives \(a = -4\), \(b = 1\) 8. \((-2, 1, 3)\) gives \(a = -2\), \(b = -5\) 9. \((-2, -1, -3)\) gives \(a = 6\), \(b = 11\) 10. \((1, 2, -3)\) gives \(a = 0\), \(b = -7\) 11. \((1, -2, 3)\) gives \(a = -2\), \(b = -5\) 12. \((-1, 2, 3)\) gives \(a = -4\), \(b = 1\) 13. \((-1, -2, -3)\) gives \(a = 6\), \(b = 11\) The unique ordered pairs \((a, b)\) are: - \((-6, -1)\) - \((-2, -5)\) - \((-4, 1)\) - \((0, -7)\) - \((6, 11)\) Thus, the number of ordered pairs \((a, b)\) is \(\boxed{5}\).
